s, UN and NGO involvement, the nature of policing, and differing concepts of professionalism and liberalization. A series of case studies—from Congo (Zaire), Eritrea, Ethiopia, Namibia, Somalia, and Uganda—inform this original book, which offers an important prism through which to view state-society relations in Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aInternal securityxCase studiesxAfricaxAfrica. 0aInternal securityzAfricavCase studies. 0aInternal securityzAfrica. 0aLaw enforcementxCase studiesxAfrica. 0aLaw enforcementzAfricavCase studies. 0aLaw enforcementzAfrica. 0aPolicexCase studiesxAfrica. 0aPolicezAfricavCase studies. 0aPolicezAfrica. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / African.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertLynne Rienner Press Complete Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311078426840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978162637412640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781626374126423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781626374126/original  a978-3-11-078426-8  Lynne Rienner Press Complete Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK